<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor=""  width="95%" align="center"><tr><td>
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1" border="0"  width="100%">
<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#DEDFDF" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post221533"></a>
	
	<font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><b>Mobutu</b></font><br>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Mostly Harmless</font><br>
	<img src="avatar.php?userid=8236&dateline=1039632290" border="0" alt=""><p>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Registered: Nov 2002<br>
	Location: St. Charles, MO<br>
	Posts: 290</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#DEDFDF" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial"> <b></b></font>
	<p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">Some of that sounds cool, but I don't know if I like the idea of "toggle abilities" in EQ.<br />
<br />
I think making healing more "fun" in EQ has more to do with re-tuning encounters rather than completely changing how heals are done.  And they have done that in places -- fights like Agnaar and Saryn with lots of adds, etc.  <br />
<br />
But I'm not sure it will be so easy.  In all reality I'd love to see a fight where no one person -- even the MT -- needed all that much healing.  This could be done by having random AE procs but low melee damage, or with tons of pure caster mobs that only cast and have to be killed in a specific order.  Mobs that move and require new tactics since they will move out of CH range at some point in fight.<br />
<br />
It also has to do with making us not be the only viable raid healers -- now, don't get me wrong druids and shamans do my guild a TON of good as patch healers and offtank healers.  But there should be no reason that all your clerics do a CHC while all your druids alternate between NI and nuking.  Additionally, they need to give each of the priest classes a special healing "niche" --  something outside the "box" of direct heals and HoT's.  Something like Clerics best at healing diseases, shamans curses, druids poisons and make encounters and events that require all three.  But you end up looking at that as needing new spell lines because as it stands Radiant Cure is > all, plus is available to all three priests and Paladins (/grrr?)<br />
<br />
As far as changing spells, I don't like the idea of toggle spells.  I think a cooler approach would be a "cooperative cast HoT" where multiple healers try to keep their HoT on the tank and the HoT's don't stack but get better as more are doing it.  Each cleric = 250 / tick, druids 200 / tick, shamans 175 / tick or something along those lines.  Maybe make it so each class only stacks with itself so you either sacrifice buff slots to have more HoT's, or you relegate some folks to doing direct heal spamming or whatnot.  <br />
<br />
I don't know the answer exactly I'm just spouting off ideas.  But the main bullet points of what they need to do are:<br />
<br />
1.  Reduce raid reliance on large number of clerics (but without trivializing content.)<br />
<br />
2.  Reduce reliance on the CH Chain. <br />
<br />
3.  Focus on encounters requiring more fluid tactics -- without relying on "higher dps" or "bigger ae's" or "stunning the clerics."<br />
<br />
4.  Revamp old content to un-trivialize it -- if we grow more powerful with experience and time, why haven't the gnolls or the orcs or the horrors in Mistmoore?  (aside from the daily genocide visited upon them by the Army of Twinks)<br />
<br />
5.  VARIETY VARIETY VARIETY!  New encounters should be more than +dps, +hp, +ae, +adds.  There has to be a way to make them unique, challenging, more than just a comparison of life and mana bars (if cleric mana > mob health, you are winning -- too simple.)  PoP did EXCELLENT in this regard, GoD...  meh.</font></p>
	
	<p><p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">__________________<br>
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=371990" target="_blank"> Mobutu Virginhunter </a><br />
Erudite Cleric of Cazic-Thule<br />
Justifiable Cause, Xegony<br />
<br />
"It's times like these I wish I'd have listened to what my mother always told me."<br />
"Why, what did your mother always tell you?"<br />
"I don't know -- I wasn't listening."</font></p></p>
